tip.text: Value for $$ at $3. Its moist but the noodles here have not absorbed the flavour of the broth. Its not bad but not a destination unlike Tian Tian Lai at Toa Payoh.

Decent steak found here. They sell wine, whisky, cheeses and charcuterie too. Parent company Habanos is a whisky and cigar distributor. Look out for the whisky masterclass.

tip.text: Decent quality and definitely value for $$, with salad bar and eggs station thrown in under $20, but I wasn't a big fan of the Hamburg steak per se which I find too mushy. An hr long queue is a norm.

Imperial treasure chains hv d most consistent quality throughout their fine dining establishments n this is no exception. In fact, many items in the menu r repetitive. Dimsum is pretty solid here too.
They tend to upsell you their products and services but to be fair, their mandarin-speaking Vietnamese therapists do a pretty good job. Massage chair with jacuzzi foot bath is a plus.

Food -more misses than hits. Had the lunch set menu ($68pp) and nothing much stood out except for the haphazard presentation which is unbecoming of hotel Chinese restaurant. Overpriced for what u get.

tip.text: New bistro in Tott is a welcome change with decent food. Carbonara ($8.9) is tasty and good value. The apple crumble dessert ($6.9) is also a nice surprise. Will try the salmon next time.

tip.text: Avoid the chirashidon set lunch. Poor value. Aburi sushi set is ok. Overall overpriced for what you get.

formattedAddress: Empress Road Market & Food Centre (7 Empress Road)

tip.text: Definitely one great option for Sunday champagne brunch found in Sg - $88++ w/o alcohol, additional $50 for Lois Roederer champagne. Highlights are the charcuterie and the 25 types of quality cheeses.
View is obviously the highlight here. 3-course set lunches available @$48++ are of decent portions and taste. Service however can be improved.

formattedAddress: #01-10 Golden Mile Food Centre (505 Beach Road)

tip.text: Tasty sheng jian bao @ $1.5 each. Big and juicy. So much like in China that u will get thirsty after.

formattedAddress: #02-02 Holland Drive Market & Food Center (Blk 44 Holland Drive)

tip.text: Reasonably priced set lunches (fr $38++) in the tanjong pagar area. Competent cooking, calm ambience and service is alright too, just nothing particularly memorable except for the flavoured salts!
Modern rendition of traditional Kueh Kuehs. Pricier than usual but worth a try.
Takes a while for me to get over the salty lei cha broth. Only if u crave for this dish when in the area.
Emphasis on West Java coffee beans, this is the sort of place that is not big on packaging but packs good flavour in their coffee. Off the beaten track in tanjong pagar area n beats Jewel hands down.
Pretty good Teochew fare. Highlight is the braised Irish duck which is very succulent. Cold crab ($90/kg) and crispy egg noodles also decent. Not a fan of the deep fried pork ball and ornee though.
What can I say? That stone staircase, wow. Just wow.
Other than the tea, the food here is surprisingly legit. Nice ambience too.

formattedAddress: Marriott Singapore Tang Plaza (320 Orchard Rd)

tip.text: Love the resort ambience over looking marriott's pool, yet u r right in the heart of orchard road. Having a meal here is almost like one is on vacation. Food is decent, hotel priced.

tip.text: The piccolo ($4) using their house blend beans has a deep robust flavour. Like!
Can find fresh artichokes here! Though not very big, it's pretty reasonably priced!

Above average Penang style Char Kway Teow. As other tippers put it succinctly, we r not in Penang and beggars can't be choosers.It's super difficult to find a decent plate of CKT, Penang style or not!

Stick to the pork (fr Hungary!) rather than the beef. Flower pot set($68) offers jowl, collar + 2 types of marinated belly. $2 for a cup of unrefillable tea, or pay the same for a flask of cold water!

tip.text: Pretty good and value-for-money 10 pax set dinners. Highlights were the suckling pig and roast duck.

tip.text: Quite dated building. Highlight should be the outdoor adventure facilities like rock climbing and abseiling. The Chinese restaurant also pretty decent.
Second visit:- Beef patty from the classic beef burger was poor. Texture is very mashy. Not ever gonna have that again.
Pretty decent rendition of an old-school bak chor mee (minced pork mushroom noodles) by an old couple. $3 for a big bowl is a steal. The pork trotter noodles look good too.
Not keen on the mock vegetarian 'meats', but the sides are ok. So is the rice. Good option for vegetarians who want alternative to the many salad shops around.
